misconceptions.name: Implemented average acceleration instead of summing even numbers
misconceptions.description:
The submitted program solves a physics average-acceleration problem rather than the assigned "sum of even numbers" problem. All core requirements of the question are therefore missing.

Rubric scoring:
- Reading 5 integers from input: 0/1 — The program reads 3 values (v0, v1, t) as doubles instead of 5 integers.
- Loop structure to process inputs: 0/1 — There is no loop; inputs are read once each with direct nextDouble() calls.
- Conditional check for even numbers (n % 2 == 0): 0/1 — There is no modulus or conditional logic to distinguish even from odd numbers.
- Accumulating sum and printing result: 0/1 — The code computes (v1 - v0) / t and prints an average acceleration message instead of accumulating a sum of even numbers and printing that.

Overall score for this question: 0/4.

Overall feedback:
- Strengths: The code is syntactically correct, uses Scanner appropriately to read input, and includes clear comments explaining the average-acceleration calculation.
- Areas for improvement: Carefully read the problem statement and ensure your code matches the required behavior. For this question, you needed to (1) read 5 integers, (2) use a loop to process them, (3) use a conditional to check for even numbers, and (4) accumulate and print the sum of only the even inputs.

Program reads three double values with nextDouble() instead of five integers with nextInt().
No loop is present to handle multiple inputs.

Output message reports average acceleration instead of the sum of even numbers.
misconceptions.root_cause: The student appears to have reused or focused on a different exercise (average acceleration from physics) and did not align their implementation with the current problem specification about summing even numbers. This reflects a misunderstanding or inattention to the requirements-to-code mapping.
misconceptions.remediation_hint: First, re-read the problem statement and restate it in your own words: "Read 5 integers and print the sum of the even ones." Then design the solution step by step: (1) Declare an int variable sum initialized to 0. (2) Use a for loop that runs 5 times, reading an int each time with nextInt(). (3) Inside the loop, use if (n % 2 == 0) to check if the number is even; if it is, add it to sum. (4) After the loop finishes, print "Sum of even numbers: " followed by sum. Keep the average-acceleration code in a separate file for that specific problem so you don’t mix tasks.
